    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-01-26T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-01-26T17:00:00-05:00" n="21"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d21">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/1–2651: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United Kingdom</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d21fn1">Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_SLL1">L.
                            Satterthwaite</persName>, Deputy Director of the Office of British
                        Commonwealth and Northern European Affairs, and cleared in draft with
                            <persName corresp="#p_MEM1">Martin</persName> (<gloss target="#t_RA1"
                            >RA</gloss>).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-01-26T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 26, 1951—5 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3539. Dept, <gloss target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss>, Def, Budget and <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> taking advantage <persName
                        corresp="#p_SCM1">Spofford</persName>’s and <persName corresp="#p_KM1"
                        >Katz</persName>’ presence US to discuss advisability of consolidating
                        <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> operations in Paris or London. Gen
                    feeling here that <persName corresp="#p_E1">Eisenhower</persName> and his staff,
                        <persName corresp="#p_SCM1">Spofford</persName> and <gloss target="#t_OEEC1"
                        >OEEC</gloss> shld be in one place and that eventually this will be found to
                    be necessary even if it is not done right away. If <gloss target="#t_SHAPE1"
                        >SHAPE</gloss> included this wld of course make it Paris. Before reaching
                    any decision on this and related problems and to help us weigh all factors, wld
                    like your estimate effect move to Paris on Brit Govt, on Brit public opinion and
                    on effectiveness Brit influence, cooperation and leadership in making defense
                    efforts successful. Text of paper covering this and other points on which we
                    want your comments will be available and sent you tomorrow with comments
                    required by Mon.<note n="2" xml:id="d21fn2">The paper referred to here has not
                        been identified in the Department of State files.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
